{"questionId":"33367042","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The graph of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>f</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;can be obtained by translating and stretching the graph of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>x</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Describe these two transformations specifying the order in which they are to be applied.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>attempt to use addition rule for logs&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mn>8</mn><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&nbsp;</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;OR&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mn>32</mn><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> &nbsp; (or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to use exponent property for logarithms&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi>x</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>the graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> must be vertically stretched (dilated) by a scale factor of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> and then vertically translated (shifted)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math> units upwards.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A2<br><br></strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p>\n<p>attempt to write argument as a power&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>32</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mfenced><msup><mfenced><mrow><msqrt><mn>32</mn></msqrt><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to use exponent property for logarithms&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><msqrt><mn>32</mn></msqrt><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p>the graph of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> must be vertically stretched (dilated) by a scale factor of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> and stretched (dilated) horizontally by a scale factor of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>32</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math>.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>the graph of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> must be stretched (dilated) horizontally by a scale factor of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>32</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math>&nbsp;and vertically stretched (dilated) by a scale factor of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>.&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1<br></strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> In this method, the final mark is <em><strong>A1</strong></em>, as the question specifically asks for a translation and a stretch.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[6 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"33367042","referenceCode":"24N.1.SL.TZ1.8d","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Describe these two transformations specifying the order in which they are to be applied.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 6]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.11—Transformation of functions","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.7—Laws of exponents and logs"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}